INSERT INTO `jos_community_events` VALUES (16,0,4,5,'group','ESC July meeting','Teleconference','Agenda:\r\nDemonstration Projects - how will these be handled in the STARS Scaling project - Tiffany, Nate, Laurie\r\nOnline community - update - Heather\r\nCelebration 2012 - preliminary thoughts; non-profit status - Teresa',45,'2011-07-11 12:00:00','2011-07-11 13:00:00',0,NULL,NULL,0,1,0,0,0,0,1,'2011-07-11 14:50:37',88,1,255,255,'Ameri','',0,NULL,'0000-00-00',NULL,NULL),(17,0,8,0,'profile','STARS New Members Workshop','Salons A&B','This is a workshop for all people (faculty, staff or students) who are serving as the Academic Liaison (AL) for their school or as the one main leader of the STARS Leadership Corps (SLC) for their school -- for the first time. This includes people at new STARS schools as well as new people at continuing STARS schools. People who are experienced in these roles are also encouraged to attend to help provide advice to the new leaders.\r\n\r\nThis goal of this workshop is to provide practical advice on how to start and manage a STARS Leadership Corps. The session will provide an overview of the STARS Leadership Corps model and outline the implementation of the Corps at UNC Charlotte as a credit-bearing servicelearning course. Materials provided include example syllabus, seminar schedule, and participant roles forms. Details and advice will be given on the practical aspects of managing a leadership corps, including organizing students, selecting projects, facilitating student team work, developing external partners, and integrating the corps into your department’s educational mission. The discussion will include lessons learned from five years of the UNC Charlotte STARS corps.',42,'2011-08-07 13:00:00','2011-08-07 16:00:00',0,NULL,NULL,0,3,0,0,0,0,0,'2011-07-28 15:24:38',86,1,255,255,'Ameri','',0,NULL,'0000-00-00',NULL,NULL),(18,0,8,0,'profile','Attracting Students to Computing with App Inventor','Boxwood/Dogwood Rooms','<p>This workshop will introduce attendees to Google\'s App Inventor which allows students to use drag-and-drop style programming to create mobile applications.  Many students and teachers are interested in creating mobile applications. We are using App Inventor in our teacher workshops and high school summer camps this summer.  We will show how to create several mobile applications using App Inventor and well as where to go for more materials.</p>\r\n<p>Presenter: Barbara Ericson, Georgia Institute of Technology</p>',42,'2011-08-07 13:00:00','2011-08-07 17:00:00',0,NULL,NULL,0,3,0,0,0,0,1,'2011-07-29 15:21:57',94,1,255,255,'Ameri','',0,NULL,'0000-00-00',NULL,NULL),(19,0,8,0,'profile','Attracting Students to Computing with CS Unplugged and Scratch','Salon C','<p>This workshop will introduce attendees to CS Unplugged and Scratch. CS Unplugged is a set of free activities that can be used to introduce students to computing concepts without using a computer. Scratch is free software from MIT that can be used to create 2D animations, interactive art, and games. Attendees will receive additional resources such as urls, slides, and pre and post surveys for measuring changes in attitudes towards computing. Georgia Tech has been using CS Unplugged and Scratch for several years and gets statistically significant positive changes in attitudes towards computing after even just a 4 hour workshop.</p>\r\n<p>Presenter: Barbara Ericson, Georgia Institute of Technology</p>',42,'2011-08-07 13:00:00','2011-08-07 17:00:00',0,NULL,NULL,0,1,0,0,0,0,1,'2011-07-29 15:25:56',87,1,13.6493,100.497,'Ameri','',0,NULL,'0000-00-00',NULL,NULL),(20,0,8,0,'profile','Pair Programming Workshop','Judicial','<p>This STARS dissemination project relates to transitioning to pair programming in the classroom. Pair programming refers to the practice whereby two programmers work together at one computer, collaborating on the same design, algorithm, code, or test. The pair is made up of a driver, who actively types at the computer or records a design; and a navigator, who watches the work of the driver and attentively identifies problems, asks clarifying questions, and makes suggestions. Both are also continuous brainstorming partners. Throughout the world, many universities are using pair programming in their computer science classes – and a number of high schools have begun using the practice as well. Generally, current-day students much prefer to collaborate than to work alone and find computer science more attractive if they are not forced to work alone the majority of the time. Between the two students, they can generally figure out most problems and can avoid pesky syntax and semantic errors that can cost many hours to debug. Perhaps during those multi-hour debugging sessions (that are greatly reduced with pair programming) some students vow to never take another computer science course! In this workshop, we will introduce pair programming; discuss research results, and issues for adoption. We will work through plans for instituting pair programming at STARS institutions and for collecting data about these experiences.</p>\r\n<p>Presenter: Laurie Williams, North Carolina State University</p>',42,'2011-08-07 15:00:00','2011-08-07 17:00:00',0,NULL,NULL,0,1,0,0,0,0,1,'2011-07-29 15:32:41',82,1,14.7,121.102,'Ameri','',0,NULL,'0000-00-00',NULL,NULL),(21,0,8,0,'profile',' Teaching Tekkotsu Robotics: Vision, Navigation, and Control','Salons D&E','<p>This hands-on workshop introduces Tekkotsu, a free, open source software framework from Carnegie Mellon that makes advanced robotics technologies accessible to undergraduates and even high school students. Tekkotsu robots use a camera to see the world, a path planner and particle filter to navigate through it, and a hierarchical, event-based, parallel state machine formalism to describe intelligent robot behaviors. Tekkotsu is the primary software framework used by the ARTSI Alliance, part of the same Broadening Participation in Computing program as STARS. Faculty interested in introducing a robotics elective in their department, or students interested in becoming involved in robotics research, are encouraged to attend. No prior robotics experience is necessary. More information about Tekkotsu robotics can be found at Tekkotsu.org and Chiara-Robot.org.</p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin-bottom: .0001pt;\">Presenter: David Touretsky, Carnegie Mellon University</p>\r\n<p> </p>',42,'2011-08-07 13:00:00','2011-08-07 17:00:00',0,NULL,NULL,0,1,0,0,0,0,1,'2011-07-29 16:13:52',87,1,255,255,'Ameri','',0,NULL,'0000-00-00',NULL,NULL),(22,0,8,0,'profile','Teaching AP CS Principles with GameMaker, Scratch, AppInventor, & StarLogo TNG','Sandalwood ','<p>Learn to help with the CS10K and AP CS Principles efforts to prepare high school teachers and students to be creators in computing! In this workshop, we will introduce the UNC Charlotte and Berkeley approach to teaching a pilot of the AP CS Principles course, called the “Beauty and Joy of Computing” (BJC). BJC invokes passion, joy, and awe through engaging students in a rigorous computing curriculum that promotes creativity and collaboration using visually rich programming environments, while also provoking thought around current events and how computing relates to people’s lives.<span style=\"mso-spacerun: yes;\"> </span>In this workshop, we’ll spend 70% of our time on various tools, where participants will experience firsthand how to conduct outreach and/or lessons with short lectures, discussions around readings, CS Unplugged activities, and a hands-on lab. We will spend 30% of our time on logistics, introducing our 16-unit curriculum, projects, and teaching methods including pair programming, along with practical tips and tricks for classes and outreach.<span style=\"mso-spacerun: yes;\"> </span>We will also discuss our “STARS” approach to engaging professors, college students, and high school teachers together to form a Computer Science Teachers Association (CSTA) partnership to enrich CS education and access in a region.</p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\">Presenters: Tiffany Barnes, Acey Boyce, Shaun Pickford, Dan Garcia, Brian Harvey</p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p> </p>',42,'2011-08-07 13:00:00','2011-08-07 17:00:00',0,NULL,NULL,0,1,0,0,0,0,1,'2011-07-29 16:17:13',124,1,-9.69934,119.974,'Ameri','',0,NULL,'0000-00-00',NULL,NULL),(23,0,8,0,'profile','Connecting your Classroom to the Community – Using Geographic Information Systems (GIS) and Global Positioning Systems (GPS) for Spatial Problem Solving','Oakwood ','<p>Involving students in real-world community issues is a powerful way to teach problem-solving skills and civicmindedness. This workshop introduces GIS and GPS to K-12 educators for use in involving students in community-based spatial problem solving. GIS in the classroom can be used to develop problem-solving skills by teaching students to (a) ask pertinent questions about their community; (b) gather data to examine those questions; (c) analyze the data and patterns; and (d) develop conclusions based on their analysis. This workshop highlights several elementary, middle and high school level GIS projects. Participants will complete a hands-on field exercise using GPS and a lab activity using GIS. The workshop concludes with a how-to guide for implementing a GIS project using free resource.</p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"> </p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\">Presenter: Katrina Simon-Agolory, Solnect Consulting Group/Wilberforce University NNSA Disaster Recovery Center</p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p> </p>',42,'2011-08-07 15:00:00','2011-08-07 17:00:00',0,NULL,NULL,0,1,0,0,0,0,1,'2011-07-29 16:19:31',88,1,255,255,'Ameri','',0,NULL,'0000-00-00',NULL,NULL),(24,0,8,0,'profile','STARS Logistics Meeting  ','Salons A&B','<p> </p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\">Required: AL from every school; optional: SLC leaders, potential new STARS</p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\">This meeting is for all people (faculty or staff) who are serving as the Academic Liaison (AL) for any of the STARS schools. People (faculty, staff or students) who are serving as the one main leader of the STARS Leadership Corps (SLC) for their school are also encouraged to attend. This meeting is for discussion of practical issues related to managing the STARS Leadership Corps and meeting the goals of the STARS Scaling project that is funded by the National Science Foundation.</p>\r\n<p> </p>',42,'2011-08-07 16:00:00','2011-08-07 17:00:00',0,NULL,NULL,0,3,0,0,1,0,1,'2011-07-29 16:43:16',88,1,255,255,'Ameri','',0,NULL,'0000-00-00',NULL,NULL),(25,0,8,0,'profile','Leadership Development','Salons F&G','<p> </p>\r\n<p>This session will connect STARS students through ice-breakers as well as leadership and team-building exercises - REQUIRED for all STARS students.</p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p>\r\n<p>Presenters: Nate Thomas, University of South Florida Polytechnic; Tierza Watts, North Carolina State University</p>\r\n</p>\r\n<p> </p>',42,'2011-08-07 18:00:00','2011-08-07 20:00:00',0,NULL,NULL,0,1,0,0,0,0,1,'2011-07-29 16:44:34',82,1,255,255,'Ameri','',0,NULL,'0000-00-00',NULL,NULL),(26,0,8,0,'profile','STARS Evaluation Assistant Training Workshop ','Salons A&B  ','<p> </p>\r\n<p>This interactive workshop will train SLC student Evaluation Assistants in conducting quantitative Broadening  Participation in Computing (BPC) research. Participants will learn and practice research skills during the workshop in preparation for their fall and spring terms as Evaluation Assistants (EAs). EAs will learn to use evaluation and reporting tools such as the SLC Activity Reporting system, the SLC Student Registration system, and will develop a strong research project for their SLC. The skills obtained in this workshop are transferable to computing research and professional development. This evaluation training workshop is required for all designated Evaluation Assistants.</p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p>Presenters: Audrey Rorrer, Kim Buch, Anthony Chow</p>\r\n<p> </p>',42,'2011-08-07 20:00:00','2011-08-07 22:00:00',0,NULL,NULL,0,2,0,0,0,0,1,'2011-07-29 16:49:54',89,1,255,255,'Ameri','',0,NULL,'0000-00-00',NULL,NULL),(27,0,8,0,'profile','STARS Annual Leaders Meeting ','Salon C ','<p> </p>\r\n<p>\r\n<hr />\r\nRequired: AL from every school</p>\r\n<p>This is the annual in-person meeting of the STARS Alliance. The Academic Liaison from each STARS school should attend.</p>\r\n<p> </p>',42,'2011-08-07 18:00:00','2011-08-07 20:00:00',0,NULL,NULL,0,5,0,0,2,0,1,'2011-07-29 16:51:26',94,1,13.6493,100.497,'Ameri','',0,NULL,'0000-00-00',NULL,NULL),(28,0,8,0,'profile','Mentoring Workshop Part I—Skills for Mentoring and Implementation  ','Boxwood','<p> </p>\r\n<p>People in higher education conduct mentoring all over the world but no one has broken down the elements of mentoring so mentors can provide effective mentoring to mentees. The Thomas Principles do that. Mentors are taught six principles (Identity Development, Social Support, Psychological Support, Academic Support, Sense of Belonging, and Leadership Development) to support mentees’ college adjustment, retention, and academic success. To ensure mentees receive appropriate mentoring, mentors are trained through a 7-hour student development workshop and yearly mentor-mentee activities. At the end of the workshop, students should leave with a strong sense of mentoring, leadership, and high expectations that promote team work, a sense of family, self efficacy, academic and personal success, service, and social change among IT and computing students.</p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p>\r\n<p>Presenter: Nate Thomas, University of South Florida Polytechnic</p>\r\n</p>\r\n<p> </p>',42,'2011-08-07 20:15:00','2011-08-07 22:15:00',0,NULL,NULL,0,1,0,0,0,0,1,'2011-07-29 16:53:32',84,1,37.4273,-79.2409,'Ameri','',0,NULL,'0000-00-00',NULL,NULL),(29,0,8,0,'profile','Mentoring Workshop (During  Breakfast) ','Salon F','<p>\r\n<p>During breakfast session school leaders meet to discuss implementation and evaluation responsibilities learned in the mentoring workshop.</p>\r\n</p>',42,'2011-08-08 08:00:00','2011-08-08 09:00:00',0,NULL,NULL,0,4,0,0,0,0,1,'2011-07-29 16:55:26',91,1,13.7713,100.618,'Ameri','',0,NULL,'0000-00-00',NULL,NULL),(30,0,8,0,'profile','Plenary Session ','Grand Ballroom 4&5','<p>\r\n<p>Welcome: Mladen Vouk, Chair of Computer Science Department, North Carolina State University</p>\r\n<p>Keynote Speaker: Annie Antón, Professor of Computer Science, North Carolina State University</p>\r\n<p>Faculty Research: 3 Minute Madness</p>\r\n</p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p> </p>',42,'2011-08-08 09:00:00','2011-08-08 10:30:00',0,NULL,NULL,0,3,0,0,0,0,1,'2011-07-29 16:56:54',85,1,255,255,'Ameri','',0,NULL,'0000-00-00',NULL,NULL),(31,0,8,0,'profile','Using Neural Networks and Fuzzy Logic to Obtain High Accuracy in Pedestrian Detection and Collision Avoidance for use in Automobiles ','Boxwood/Dogwood Rooms ','<p> </p>\r\n<p>Modern technology has afforded the average man with several luxuries. Smart car technologies such as Intelligent Cruise Control, Blind Spot Detection and Advanced Parking Guidance Systems have been created to aid the prevention of human error when drivers operate a vehicle. In the future, the idea of having your vehicle autonomously drive itself would become as every day as using the microwave. Research into highly automated cognitive and control techniques have been engineered to relieve drivers from the mundane moment-to-moment decision making involved in driving. Researchers such as those at VisLab at Parma University have invented fully autonomous vehicles like BRAiVE (BRAin-drIVE) which perform pedestrian detection and avoidance. Other researchers have even created vehicles that can “pick you up” like the autonomous taxi in Germany created by the AutoNOMOS team which is part of the Artificial Intelligence Group of the Freie Universität Berlin. Unfortunately, these systems do not take into consideration times when, in the regrettable instance, that while the vehicle autonomously navigates towards its user, it realizes that collision with a human or another car or a combination of both is inevitable due to unforeseen situations. Research has not been published that allows a vehicle to make this decision when its user is not present. Therefore, this system seeks to make use of artificial intelligence techniques such as fuzzy logic and neural networks to make this distinction and therefore improve pedestrian detection within smart vehicles.</p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p>\r\n<p>Presenters: Sihle Wilson, Jason Black, Florida A&M University</p>\r\n</p>\r\n<p> </p>',42,'2011-08-08 10:30:00','2011-08-08 11:30:00',0,NULL,NULL,0,2,0,0,0,0,1,'2011-07-29 16:59:26',88,1,255,255,'Ameri','',0,NULL,'0000-00-00',NULL,NULL),(32,0,8,0,'profile','DISS - A Context-Aware, Platform-Independent System Designed to  Improve Autonomous and Manual Automobile Navigation ','Boxwood/Dogwood Room','<p> </p>\r\n<p>Navigation systems are becoming a staple of automobile travel in today’s world. Dedicated GPS units as well as GPS equipped mobile devices such as smart phones, mp3 players, and tablet computers are the tool of choice for many drivers when the need for help navigating from one place to another, rendering traditional paper maps all but obsolete. However, the downside to all of the previously mentioned navigation systems is the lack of total route accuracy. GPS routes are often inefficient and sometimes even erroneous, which is a burden for a person manually driving a car, and potentially calamitous for the autonomous cars of the future. Often, it seems that the best method of finding one’s way from one place to another is to follow the directions of an individual who knows and physically traversed the area in question. This talk presents the Distributed Information Sharing System, or DISS for short. DISS is a context aware system employing a cross-platform mobile application interface which allows for drivers to share driving information that isn’t available in standard GPS and maps services, information which can then be shared with other cars employing the system, hopefully making road navigation more efficient.</p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p>\r\n<p>Presenters: Ronald Benson, Jason Black, Florida A&M University</p>\r\n</p>\r\n<p> </p>',42,'2011-08-08 10:30:00','2011-08-08 11:30:00',0,NULL,NULL,0,1,0,0,0,0,1,'2011-07-29 17:05:04',85,1,255,255,'Ameri','',0,NULL,'0000-00-00',NULL,NULL),(33,0,8,0,'profile','Games + Learning Research Spotlight ','Salons A,B,C ','<p> </p>\r\n<p>Play is something all mammals do, and it serves two purposes: to practice for real situations, and to bring us closer to one another. Modern video games can help people both play to learn, and come together with others around play. In the Games + Learning Lab at UNC Charlotte, we explore these facets of play and learning through developing and evaluating games that integrate play and sociality. Come be the first to see some of UNC Charlotte\'s work around mobile, social, and educational games, and the tools we use to understand our players and learners.</p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p>\r\n<p>Presenter: Tiffany Barnes, University of North Carolina at Charlotte</p>\r\n</p>\r\n<p> </p>',42,'2011-08-08 10:30:00','2011-08-08 11:30:00',0,NULL,NULL,0,2,0,0,0,0,1,'2011-07-29 17:10:10',82,1,255,255,'Ameri','',0,NULL,'0000-00-00',NULL,NULL),(34,0,8,0,'profile','Creating Optimal Conditions for High Performing Undergraduate Research Experiences—Part I ','Salons D&E','<p> </p>\r\n<p>In an interactive way, learn about how to start-up high quality REU environments where students are fully engaged in their project while intentionally providing structured research skills and communication/team skills development that will contribute to their future success. Longitudinal studies of this approach show high retention and high rates of underrepresented students choosing the grad school pathway. The \"Affinity Research Group (ARG)\" model will be the focus of this session and will be continued in session II. Especially designed for anyone involved in leading REU initiatives. Sponsored by A4RC.</p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p>\r\n<p>Presenter: Maureen Biggers, A4RC Co-PI and Program Manager</p>\r\n</p>\r\n<p> </p>',42,'2011-08-08 10:30:00','2011-08-08 11:30:00',0,NULL,NULL,0,2,0,0,0,0,1,'2011-07-29 17:11:52',88,1,255,255,'Ameri','',0,NULL,'0000-00-00',NULL,NULL),(35,0,8,0,'profile','Ad Hoc Session','Congressional','<div style=\"color: #333333; font-family: Tahoma, Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 76%; background-image: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; background-color: #ffffff; line-height: 1.3em; margin: 8px;\">\r\n<p>\r\n<p style=\"line-height: 15.6pt; background: white;\"><span style=\"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: &quot;Tahoma&quot;,&quot;sans-serif&quot;; color: #333333;\">In addition to the scheduled sessions, you are welcome to organize extended talks, panel discussions or work groups (birds-of-a-feather) in one of the conference’s ad-hoc sessions. These sessions are in response to ideas and issues that have been nagging you or issues and questions that arise during the conference.</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"line-height: 15.6pt; background: white;\"><span style=\"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: &quot;Tahoma&quot;,&quot;sans-serif&quot;; color: #333333;\">To request and ad hoc session, fill out an ad hoc session request form and return it to the registration desk. Ad hoc sessions my be “clinics”, where you bring a problem for which you would like input.  For example, would you like assistance in developing an evaluation tool for a community outreach program? Other suggestions include topics from the conference you would like to discuss further or unscheduled topics that you would like to share at the conference.</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"line-height: 15.6pt; background: white;\"><span style=\"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: &quot;Tahoma&quot;,&quot;sans-serif&quot;; color: #333333;\">Ad hoc session requests will be displayed near the registration tables. Attendees indicate interest in the topic by signing up for the session.  If enough interest is shown, the session will be scheduled in one of the “ad hoc session” rooms. These will be announced at the plenary session in the morning and will be displayed near the registration table.</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"> </p>\r\n</p>\r\n</div>',42,'2011-08-08 10:30:00','2011-08-08 11:30:00',0,NULL,NULL,0,1,0,0,0,0,1,'2011-07-29 17:12:48',75,1,40.4265,-111.758,'Ameri','',0,NULL,'0000-00-00',NULL,NULL),(36,0,8,0,'profile','Virtual Educational Communities Supported with Cloud Computing','Boxwood/Dogwood Rooms ','<p>This research paper reports preliminary results of a survey to improve the group practice of educational communities and provide a tool to support their sharing of best practices and is in line with CSCW research. The surveyed system was developed for Communities of Practice members to share content material, supportive materials, animated examples, videos, pod casts and other technology with the promise of increasing the collective intelligence of the community in this synergistic effort.  This work redesigns a collaborative tool and tests it as a work space for sharing all types of educational material analogous to Blackboard for college groups. The challenge was to provide easy, secure access to our study populations for this endeavor. These groups include: K-12 students and teachers, community groups, 4-H units, clubs, farmers and an expert group (serving as a control group). The communities of practice have many levels of users within them, with diverse levels of expertise thus requiring a tool that doesn\'t have a learning curve among novice users. Before settling on this tool, we conducted a mini survey on the several educational virtual communities to determine their effectiveness and accessibility as pedagogical agents. Based on the feedback from users on the previous tools, we settled on a cloud tool which is utilized in this study because of it has improved interfaces compared to the previous Bulletin Board tool used in our previous study. The survey questions focus on usability. The responses are from an expert group who approve the cloud tool for collaboration within communities of practice with an average score of a 5.6 on a 7 point scale.</p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p>\r\n<p>Presenters: Cheryl Seals, Justus Nyagwencha, Albanie Bolton; Auburn University</p>\r\n</p>',42,'2011-08-08 11:30:00','2011-08-08 12:30:00',0,NULL,NULL,0,2,0,0,0,0,1,'2011-07-29 17:16:19',78,1,255,255,'Ameri','',0,NULL,'0000-00-00',NULL,NULL),(37,0,8,0,'profile','Worldwide Earthquake Detectors: Where Computing Helps Survival! ','Boxwood/Dogwood Rooms','<p> </p>\r\n<p>In the wake of recent earthquakes in Japan, a lot of speculation is underway if the solutions for earthquake prediction are right enough or at which stage do they actually begin to generate information that helps. An insight into the present system to understand what possibly could be changed to make these computations faster and more reliable.</p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p>Presenter: Preeti Syal, North Carolina State University</p>\r\n<p> </p>',42,'2011-08-08 11:30:00','2011-08-08 12:30:00',0,NULL,NULL,0,1,0,0,0,0,1,'2011-07-29 17:18:10',81,1,255,255,'Ameri','',0,NULL,'0000-00-00',NULL,NULL),(38,0,8,0,'profile','Creating a Masters in IT program ','Boxwood/Dogwood Room','<p> </p>\r\n<p>STARS students performed research on student choices, industry competition, program design, and delivery method. Students also examined local and regional schools to compare syllabi and concentrations.  Data from the research was used in the Masters in IT proposal submitted to the Florida Board of Governors. FSU is planning to launch a Master\'s program in IT this coming fall.</p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p>Presenters: Eli Pearl, Louie Garofalo, Ebe Randeree; Florida State University</p>\r\n<p> </p>',42,'2011-08-08 11:30:00','2011-08-08 12:30:00',0,NULL,NULL,0,2,0,0,0,0,1,'2011-07-29 17:20:01',64,1,255,255,'Ameri','',0,NULL,'0000-00-00',NULL,NULL),(39,0,8,0,'profile','Game Maker Outreach','Salons A,B,C','<p> </p>\r\n<p>Many middle and high school students become interested in computing due to their enjoyment of video games. These students often desire to play a role in video game design and development. By exposing students to simple tools for creating video games, we can help to focus their interests early and inspire them about computer science. In this workshop, participants will learn how to run outreach using the Game Maker software by taking part in an example tutorial. We will walk attendees through the creation of a simple game called \"Catch the Clown,\" an activity that has been used with great success in middle and high schools. We will also introduce the Bead Loom Game, a game we designed to teach iteration and math while promoting creativity.  We will also discuss how to extend this session into long term outreach. Participants are encouraged to bring their own laptops with Game Maker installed so they can follow along with the tutorial.</p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p>\r\n<p>Presenter: Acey Boyce, University of North Carolina at Charlotte</p>\r\n</p>\r\n<p> </p>',42,'2011-08-08 11:30:00','2011-08-08 12:30:00',0,NULL,NULL,0,2,0,0,0,0,1,'2011-07-29 17:22:04',79,1,255,255,'Ameri','',0,NULL,'0000-00-00',NULL,NULL),(40,0,8,0,'profile','Creating Optimal Conditions for High Performing Undergraduate Research Experiences—Part II ','Salons D&E','<p> </p>\r\n<p>Session I introduced a great working model and participants experienced how to get things started with using it.  This session will continue the discussion with activities that demonstrate what to do as time passes to maintain engagement while providing a variety of research and professional development skills for your students. Also to be introduced is the new NCWIT REU-In-a-Box resource.  Especially designed for anyone involved in leading REU initiatives. Sponsored by A4RC.</p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p>\r\n<p>Presenter: Maureen Biggers, A4RC Co-PI and Program Manager</p>\r\n</p>\r\n<p> </p>',42,'2011-08-08 11:30:00','2011-08-08 12:30:00',0,NULL,NULL,0,2,0,0,0,0,1,'2011-07-29 17:23:41',80,1,255,255,'Ameri','',0,NULL,'0000-00-00',NULL,NULL),(41,0,8,0,'profile','Ad Hoc Session','Congressional','<p>\r\n<p style=\"line-height: 15.6pt; background: white;\"><span style=\"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: &quot;Tahoma&quot;,&quot;sans-serif&quot;; color: #333333;\">In addition to the scheduled sessions, you are welcome to organize extended talks, panel discussions or work groups (birds-of-a-feather) in one of the conference’s ad-hoc sessions. These sessions are in response to ideas and issues that have been nagging you or issues and questions that arise during the conference.</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"line-height: 15.6pt; background: white;\"><span style=\"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: &quot;Tahoma&quot;,&quot;sans-serif&quot;; color: #333333;\">To request and ad hoc session, fill out an ad hoc session request form and return it to the registration desk. Ad hoc sessions my be “clinics”, where you bring a problem for which you would like input.  For example, would you like assistance in developing an evaluation tool for a community outreach program? Other suggestions include topics from the conference you would like to discuss further or unscheduled topics that you would like to share at the conference.</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"line-height: 15.6pt; background: white;\"><span style=\"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: &quot;Tahoma&quot;,&quot;sans-serif&quot;; color: #333333;\">Ad hoc session requests will be displayed near the registration tables. Attendees indicate interest in the topic by signing up for the session.  If enough interest is shown, the session will be scheduled in one of the “ad hoc session” rooms. These will be announced at the plenary session in the morning and will be displayed near the registration table.</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"> </