search Discussion','Salons D&E ','<p>\r\n<p>Faculty roundtable will exchange ideas about research collaboration, tenure, grant applications and whatever anyone wants to bring to the table.</p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n</p>',42,'2011-08-08 13:30:00','2011-08-08 14:30:00',0,NULL,NULL,0,1,0,0,0,0,1,'2011-07-29 17:29:22',81,1,255,255,'Ameri','',0,NULL,'0000-00-00',NULL,NULL),(45,0,8,0,'profile','Ad Hoc Session','Congressional','<p> </p>\r\n<p style=\"line-height: 15.6pt; background: white;\"><span style=\"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: &quot;Tahoma&quot;,&quot;sans-serif&quot;; color: #333333;\">In addition to the scheduled sessions, you are welcome to organize extended talks, panel discussions or work groups (birds-of-a-feather) in one of the conference’s ad-hoc sessions. These sessions are in response to ideas and issues that have been nagging you or issues and questions that arise during the conference.</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"line-height: 15.6pt; background: white;\"><span style=\"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: &quot;Tahoma&quot;,&quot;sans-serif&quot;; color: #333333;\">To request and ad hoc session, fill out an ad hoc session request form and return it to the registration desk. Ad hoc sessions my be “clinics”, where you bring a problem for which you would like input.  For example, would you like assistance in developing an evaluation tool for a community outreach program? Other suggestions include topics from the conference you would like to discuss further or unscheduled topics that you would like to share at the conference.</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"line-height: 15.6pt; background: white;\"><span style=\"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: &quot;Tahoma&quot;,&quot;sans-serif&quot;; color: #333333;\">Ad hoc session requests will be displayed near the registration tables. Attendees indicate interest in the topic by signing up for the session.  If enough interest is shown, the session will be scheduled in one of the “ad hoc session” rooms. These will be announced at the plenary session in the morning and will be displayed near the registration table.</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"> </p>\r\n<p> </p>',42,'2011-08-08 13:30:00','2011-08-08 14:30:00',0,NULL,NULL,0,1,0,0,0,0,1,'2011-07-29 17:31:05',80,1,40.4265,-111.758,'Ameri','',0,NULL,'0000-00-00',NULL,NULL),(46,0,8,0,'profile','Graduate School: How, When & Why from Experience ',' Boxwood/Dogwood Room','<p> </p>\r\n<p>STARS Celebration attracts hundreds of Undergraduate students every year. Many of these students are looking for graduate schools, and need information on how to apply, where to apply, what to expect, how to pay fees, etc. It is always difficult to deliver all that information in one presentation or panel session. This session is designed based on moderated panel concept, where 5-7 graduate students/graduate advisors will be answer questions raised by prospective students for graduate studies. We will bring different panelists to specifically address different aspects of graduate life, thus maximizing the information delivered. At the end the panelists will be meet the students in groups to interact on one-to-one basis.</p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p>\r\n<p>Presenter: Kashif Sharif, University of North Carolina at Charlotte</p>\r\n</p>\r\n<p> </p>',42,'2011-08-08 14:30:00','2011-08-08 15:30:00',0,NULL,NULL,0,1,0,0,0,0,1,'2011-07-29 19:09:52',81,1,255,255,'Ameri','',0,NULL,'0000-00-00',NULL,NULL),(47,0,8,0,'profile',' Intro to Typesetting using LaTeX',' Salons A,B,C','<p> </p>\r\n<p>LaTeX is a document preparation system for high-quality typesetting. It is widely used by mathematicians, scientists and researchers in academia. Most research papers submitted at conferences are written using LaTeX. LaTeX != Word Processor Instead, it encourages authors not to worry about the appearance of their documents but to concentrate on getting the right content. Using LaTeX for the first time can be challenging. This hands-on presentation provides an introduction to LaTeX as well as some tips and tricks that one might struggle to find in the documentation. Attendees will be able to work on a live LaTeX document!</p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p>Presenter: Trisha Biswas, North Carolina State University</p>\r\n<p> </p>',42,'2011-08-08 14:30:00','2011-08-08 15:30:00',0,NULL,NULL,0,2,0,0,0,0,1,'2011-07-29 19:11:23',75,1,255,255,'Ameri','',0,NULL,'0000-00-00',NULL,NULL),(48,0,8,0,'profile','Designing and Critiquing Research  Posters','Salons D&E','<p> </p>\r\n<p>This interactive session will explore content elements, design and participants be grouped in small teams to step into the role of a poster judge using judging rubrics and sharing observations and providing feedback. We\'ll have sample posters, but anyone with a research poster is welcome to bring it to this session to receive feedback! Sponsored by A4RC.</p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p>Presenters: A4RC Representatives</p>\r\n<p> </p>',42,'2011-08-08 14:30:00','2011-08-08 15:30:00',0,NULL,NULL,0,1,0,0,0,0,1,'2011-07-29 19:12:57',79,1,255,255,'Ameri','',0,NULL,'0000-00-00',NULL,NULL),(49,0,8,0,'profile','Ad Hoc Session','Congressional','<p>\r\n<p style=\"line-height: 15.6pt; background: white;\"><span style=\"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: &quot;Tahoma&quot;,&quot;sans-serif&quot;; color: #333333;\">In addition to the scheduled sessions, you are welcome to organize extended talks, panel discussions or work groups (birds-of-a-feather) in one of the conference’s ad-hoc sessions. These sessions are in response to ideas and issues that have been nagging you or issues and questions that arise during the conference.</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"line-height: 15.6pt; background: white;\"><span style=\"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: &quot;Tahoma&quot;,&quot;sans-serif&quot;; color: #333333;\">To request and ad hoc session, fill out an ad hoc session request form and return it to the registration desk. Ad hoc sessions my be “clinics”, where you bring a problem for which you would like input.  For example, would you like assistance in developing an evaluation tool for a community outreach program? Other suggestions include topics from the conference you would like to discuss further or unscheduled topics that you would like to share at the conference.</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"line-height: 15.6pt; background: white;\"><span style=\"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: &quot;Tahoma&quot;,&quot;sans-serif&quot;; color: #333333;\">Ad hoc session requests will be displayed near the registration tables. Attendees indicate interest in the topic by signing up for the session.  If enough interest is shown, the session will be scheduled in one of the “ad hoc session” rooms. These will be announced at the plenary session in the morning and will be displayed near the registration table.</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"> </p>\r\n</p>',42,'2011-08-08 14:30:00','2011-08-08 15:30:00',0,NULL,NULL,0,1,0,0,0,0,1,'2011-07-29 19:15:39',77,1,40.4265,-111.758,'Ameri','',0,NULL,'0000-00-00',NULL,NULL),(50,0,8,0,'profile','A Teacher for Every Learner: Intelligent Natural Language Tutoring Systems','Boxwood/Dogwood Rooms','<p> </p>\r\n<p>Artificial intelligence technologies contribute to many aspects of our society. In education, intelligent systems can help students learn by adaptively presenting material and enabling problem-solving episodes that are individually customized for each student. This talk presents an overview of one type of intelligent system for education, called a tutorial dialogue system, which engages students in one-on-one natural language dialogue similar to working with a human tutor. We discuss some ways in which today’s data-driven artificial intelligence research methods, such as machine learning and statistical models, can help to determine how a tutorial dialogue system should behave. Finally, we take a look at promising future work that aims to provide students with access to affordable, adaptive intelligent systems for learning.</p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p>Presenter: Kristy Boyer, North Carolina State University</p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p> </p>',42,'2011-08-08 15:30:00','2011-08-08 16:30:00',0,NULL,NULL,0,1,0,0,0,0,1,'2011-07-29 19:17:11',82,1,255,255,'Ameri','',0,NULL,'0000-00-00',NULL,NULL),(51,0,8,0,'profile','Undergraduate Student Research Birds-of-a-Feather','Salons A,B,C','<p> </p>\r\n<p>This session is for students only and is an open and frank discussion with students who have recently participated in research experiences either as summer interns or in their home departments during the academic year. Hear their stories about what they expected; what it was really like; their challenges; what they learned; what they might have done differently if they could start it again; their advice. Bring questions and enjoy! Sponsored by A4RC.</p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p>Presenters: A4RC sponsored student participants</p>\r\n<p> </p>',42,'2011-08-08 15:30:00','2011-08-08 16:30:00',0,NULL,NULL,0,2,0,0,0,0,1,'2011-07-29 19:18:43',82,1,255,255,'Ameri','',0,NULL,'0000-00-00',NULL,NULL),(52,0,8,0,'profile','Serving Girls Globally: U.S. STARS Can Create High Hopes in Haiti ','Salons D&E','<p> </p>\r\n<p>There is extensive evidence that computer skills, English and vocational education for high school girls can help change Haiti\'s future. Yet, these opportunities are simply not being provided. The High Hopes Haiti project of Charlotte-based non-profit Mothering Across continents is working to fill the void, beginning with a leadership, mentoring and computer literacy program in rural, Northern Haiti. The challenge is how best to develop a curriculum that can excite and engage about one hundred 11th and 12th grade girls in computer learning/literacy. This presentation will \"introduce\" STARS to these young women via photos and stories, and invite you to become involved.</p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p>Presenter: Courtney Jackson</p>\r\n<p> </p>',42,'2011-08-08 15:30:00','2011-08-08 16:30:00',0,NULL,NULL,0,2,0,0,11,0,1,'2011-07-29 19:20:27',82,1,255,255,'Ameri','',0,NULL,'0000-00-00',NULL,NULL