Relationships','Salon F','<p>\r\n<p>Presenter: Nate Thomas, University of South Florida Polytechnic</p>\r\n</p>',42,'2011-08-08 15:30:00','2011-08-08 16:30:00',0,NULL,NULL,0,1,0,0,0,0,1,'2011-07-29 19:21:52',69,1,13.7713,100.618,'Ameri','',0,NULL,'0000-00-00',NULL,NULL),(55,0,8,0,'profile','Plenary Session','Grand Ballroom','<p> </p>\r\n<p>Keynote Speaker: “The Three C’s to Win in Today’s Economic Environment,” Daniel Thompson, President and CEO at I-Cubed</p>\r\n<p>Poster Introductions: 30 second madness</p>\r\n<p> </p>',42,'2011-08-09 09:00:00','2011-08-09 10:30:00',0,NULL,NULL,0,2,0,0,0,0,1,'2011-07-29 19:22:56',85,1,44.9404,-123.037,'Ameri','',0,NULL,'0000-00-00',NULL,NULL),(56,0,8,0,'profile','Poster Session','Grand Ballroom 1-3 ','',42,'2011-08-09 10:30:00','2011-08-09 12:00:00',0,NULL,NULL,0,3,0,0,0,0,1,'2011-07-29 19:23:58',81,1,44.9404,-123.037,'Ameri','',0,NULL,'0000-00-00',NULL,NULL),(57,0,8,0,'profile','Lunch- 5x5: Five Professionals List the Top Five Things You Should Learn in College to Succeed in Your Career  ','Grand Ballroom 4-5','',42,'2011-08-09 12:00:00','2011-08-09 13:00:00',0,NULL,NULL,0,1,0,0,0,0,1,'2011-07-29 19:25:22',76,1,44.9404,-123.037,'Ameri','',0,NULL,'0000-00-00',NULL,NULL),(58,0,8,0,'profile','How I Got Here: Life Stories of Successful Computing Professionals','Boxwood/Dogwood Rooms ','<p>\r\n<p>During this panel, several industry representatives will give brief (five- to ten-minute) versions of their life stories. They will describe where they came from, how they became interested in computing or IT, and the education and career path they took to get there. This panel will be of interest to both undergraduate and graduate students as they look forward to starting their careers. Approximately 30 minutes will be devoted to the panelists\' biographies, with the remaining time for question/answers from the audience.</p>\r\n</p>',42,'2011-08-09 13:00:00','2011-08-09 14:00:00',0,NULL,NULL,0,1,0,0,0,0,1,'2011-07-29 19:28:14',78,1,255,255,'Ameri','',0,NULL,'0000-00-00',NULL,NULL),(59,0,8,0,'profile','Researching Your Outreach','Salons A,B,C','<p> </p>\r\n<p>This workshop will demonstrate how to conduct Broadening Participation in Computing (BPC) research from SLC Outreach Projects. Participants will learn  how to apply research skills and practices to SLC outreach, along with how to contribute to the body of BPC literature through publications. Successful research projects will be demonstrated and discussed.</p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p>Presenter: Tiffany Barnes, University of North Carolina at Charlotte</p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p> </p>',42,'2011-08-09 13:00:00','2011-08-09 14:00:00',0,NULL,NULL,0,1,0,0,0,0,1,'2011-07-29 19:31:05',80,1,255,255,'Ameri','',0,NULL,'0000-00-00',NULL,NULL),(60,0,8,0,'profile','Attitudes Towards Computer Science and Information Technology','Salons D&E ','<p> </p>\r\n<p>The NSF sponsored New Image in Computing project conducted a national survey of 1,406 youth 13-17 years old (32% were black or African American, 28% Latino/Hispanic) about their computing attitudes and college degree preferences. Major findings included that most college bound males had a favorable opinion of pursuing CS as a major, black and Hispanic college bound males had a higher interest in CS than all other groups, and the females, regardless of age or race, were significantly less interested in pursuing CS as a college major. The presentation will discuss major results of the study, supplemented by additional literature on this topic, and implications for marketing and recruitment.</p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p>\r\n<p>Presenter: Anthony Chow, University of North Carolina at Greensboro</p>\r\n</p>\r\n<p> </p>',42,'2011-08-09 13:00:00','2011-08-09 14:00:00',0,NULL,NULL,0,2,0,0,0,0,1,'2011-07-29 19:32:27',86,1,255,255,'Ameri','',0,NULL,'0000-00-00',NULL,NULL),(61,0,8,0,'profile','Ad Hoc Session','Congressional','<p>\r\n<p style=\"line-height: 15.6pt; background: white;\"><span style=\"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: &quot;Tahoma&quot;,&quot;sans-serif&quot;; color: #333333;\">In addition to the scheduled sessions, you are welcome to organize extended talks, panel discussions or work groups (birds-of-a-feather) in one of the conference’s ad-hoc sessions. These sessions are in response to ideas and issues that have been nagging you or issues and questions that arise during the conference.</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"line-height: 15.6pt; background: white;\"><span style=\"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: &quot;Tahoma&quot;,&quot;sans-serif&quot;; color: #333333;\">To request and ad hoc session, fill out an ad hoc session request form and return it to the registration desk. Ad hoc sessions my be “clinics”, where you bring a problem for which you would like input.  For example, would you like assistance in developing an evaluation tool for a community outreach program? Other suggestions include topics from the conference you would like to discuss further or unscheduled topics that you would like to share at the conference.</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"line-height: 15.6pt; background: white;\"><span style=\"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: &quot;Tahoma&quot;,&quot;sans-serif&quot;; color: #333333;\">Ad hoc session requests will be displayed near the registration tables. Attendees indicate interest in the topic by signing up for the session.  If enough interest is shown, the session will be scheduled in one of the “ad hoc session” rooms. These will be announced at the plenary session in the morning and will be displayed near the registration table.</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"> </p>\r\n</p>',42,'2011-08-09 13:00:00','2011-08-09 14:00:00',0,NULL,NULL,0,1,0,0,0,0,1,'2011-07-29 19:33:00',76,1,40.4265,-111.758,'Ameri','',0,NULL,'0000-00-00',NULL,NULL),(62,0,8,0,'profile','Discovering Your Colors: Personal Styles and Their Impact on Team and Leadership ','Boxwood/Dogwood Room','<p> </p>\r\n<p>A short survey will help you identify your primary and secondary colors with respect to your interpersonal style when interacting with others.  Hear how you may be impacting others around you and vice versa, and how to better understand people who are different from yourself.  See how a diversity of styles contributes significantly to high performing teams. (Note:  Research shows that only 30% of success of managers is attributed to technical expertise - the rest is all about emotional intelligence and this session relates to emotional intelligence!).  Sponsored by A4RC.</p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p>\r\n<p>Presenter: Maureen Biggers, A4RC Co-PI and Program Manager</p>\r\n</p>\r\n<p> </p>',42,'2011-08-09 14:00:00','2011-08-09 15:00:00',0,NULL,NULL,0,1,0,0,0,0,1,'2011-07-29 19:34:18',83,1,255,255,'Ameri','',0,NULL,'0000-00-00',NULL,NULL),(63,0,8,0,'profile','Effectiveness of Cognitive Apprenticeship Learning (CAL) and  Cognitive Tutors (CT) for Problem Solving Using Fundamental Programming Concepts ',' Salons A,B,C','<p> </p>\r\n<p>We describe our approach in addressing learning challenges students experience in introductory programming courses. We combine two effective instructional methodologies to help students learn to plan programs prior to writing code: Cognitive Apprenticeship Learning (CAL) and Cognitive Tutors (CT). In the CAL component, the instructor models program planning in class and paper handouts are used to scaffold program planning in homework assignments. In CALCT, the program planning process is also supported by a computer tutor which provides step-by-step feedback and advice. The results show that the combined CAL-CT approach yielded substantial gains over traditional instruction. Its advantage over the CALOnly approach is also significant. Anecdotal evidences and surveys also give very positive evidence. After students used tutors for one concept, they often ask for tutors for other concepts. The majority of students expressed that these tutors helped make the course more enjoyable,helped them learn faster and at a higher level, and improved their motivation.</p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p>Presenter: Wei Jin, Shaw University</p>',42,'2011-08-09 14:00:00','2011-08-09 15:00:00',0,NULL,NULL,0,1,0,0,0,0,1,'2011-07-29 19:35:59',88,1,255,255,'Ameri','',0,NULL,'0000-00-00',NULL,NULL),(64,0,8,0,'profile','Georgia Computes! - Impacting  From 4th Grade to Undergraduate ',' Salons D&E','<p>This presentation will discuss Georgia Computes! which is a NSF BPC alliance that aims to improve computing education in Georgia along all stages of the pipeline from 4th grade to undergraduate education.  It will provide detail on the activities Georgia Computes! has tried which include teacher workshops, summer camps, weekend computing workshops with youth serving organizations, after-school workshops, competitions, a lending library and more.  It will also give a summary of the research results from these activities.  Georgia Computes! has had success with attracting more students to computing and with changing attitudes towards computing.</p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p>\r\n<p>Presenter: Barbara Ericson, Georgia Institute of Technology</p>\r\n</p>',42,'2011-08-09 14:00:00','2011-08-09 15:00:00',0,NULL,NULL,0,1,0,0,0,0,1,'2011-07-29 19:37:43',84,1,255,255,'Ameri','',0,NULL,'0000-00-00',NULL,NULL),(65,0,8,0,'profile','Ad Hoc Session','Congressional','<p>\r\n<p style=\"line-height: 15.6pt; background: white;\"><span style=\"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: &quot;Tahoma&quot;,&quot;sans-serif&quot;; color: #333333;\">In addition to the scheduled sessions, you are welcome to organize extended talks, panel discussions or work groups (birds-of-a-feather) in one of the conference’s ad-hoc sessions. These sessions are in response to ideas and issues that have been nagging you or issues and questions that arise during the conference.</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"line-height: 15.6pt; background: white;\"><span style=\"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: &quot;Tahoma&quot;,&quot;sans-serif&quot;; color: #333333;\">To request and ad hoc session, fill out an ad hoc session request form and return it to the registration desk. Ad hoc sessions my be “clinics”, where you bring a problem for which you would like input.  For example, would you like assistance in developing an evaluation tool for a community outreach program? Other suggestions include topics from the conference you would like to discuss further or unscheduled topics that you would like to share at the conference.</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"line-height: 15.6pt; background: white;\"><span style=\"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: &quot;Tahoma&quot;,&quot;sans-serif&quot;; color: #333333;\">Ad hoc session requests will be displayed near the registration tables. Attendees indicate interest in the topic by signing up for the session.  If enough interest is shown, the session will be scheduled in one of the “ad hoc session” rooms. These will be announced at the plenary session in the morning and will be displayed near the registration table.</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"> </p>\r\n</p>',42,'2011-08-09 14:00:00','2011-08-09 15:00:00',0,NULL,NULL,0,1,0,0,0,0,1,'2011-07-29 19:39:07',84,1,40.4265,-111.758,'Ameri','',0,NULL,'0000-00-00',NULL,NULL),(66,0,8,0,'profile','Personal Privacy Management','Boxwood/Dogwood Rooms','<p>A variety of online and mobile applications allow people to post and share photos and documents, personal and contact information, relationships with people and organizations, and location and activities. The goal of all of these applications is to allow people to share useful information with each other for social benefits, and with organizations for customized and useful services. Yet, users are required to act as administrators for all of their own data, managing who can access which pieces of information in which circumstances. On one hand, users can seem oblivious to their privacy, doing little to protect their personal data. On the other hand, there has been much media coverage and even consumer backlash over privacy issues. In this talk, I will present the results of several of my research projects aimed at understanding and addressing the privacy needs of users. I will talk about the results of several studies of online privacy, particularly on Facebook, and several new interfaces to address privacy problems that we have designed.</p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p>\r\n<p>Presenter: Heather Richter Lipford, University of North Carolina at Charlotte</p>\r\n</p>',42,'2011-08-09 15:00:00','2011-08-09 16:00:00',0,NULL,NULL,0,2,0,0,0,0,1,'2011-07-29 19:41:13',90,1,255,255,'Ameri','',0,NULL,'0000-00-00',NULL,NULL),(67,0,8,0,'profile','Leveraging SLC to Attract Funding','Salons A,B,C ','<p>The outcomes of the STARS Alliance’ four-year study of 20 colleges and universities provides powerful evidence of the impact of the STARS Leadership Corps (SLC) for student retention and advancement. In the Diversity in Information Technology Institute at UNC Charlotte, we have funded a set of computing pipeline programs that leverage the SLC for recruitment, mentoring and skills development of students. In this session, we describe our approach for levering the SLC to attract funding in three key ways: 1) for recruitment and mentoring to attract student scholarships; 2) to broaden the impact of computing research projects; and 3) to attract donor support. This interactive session will invite other schools to share their success with leveraging the SLC to attract funding.</p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p>\r\n<p>Presenter: Teresa Dahlberg, University of North Carolina at Charlotte</p>\r\n</p>',42,'2011-08-09 15:00:00','2011-08-09 16:00:00',0,NULL,NULL,0,1,0,0,0,0,1,'2011-07-29 19:42:34',77,1,255,255,'Ameri','',0,NULL,'0000-00-00',NULL,NULL),(68,0,8,0,'profile','Partnering with TSA','Salons D&E','<p>Technology Student Association (TSA) is a national, non-profit student organization for middle and high school students who have a strong interest in technology.  The objective of the STARS Alliance at Florida State University is to introduce this organization to more middle school students. STARS students attended and led breakout sessions with students at the annual TSA Leadership Conference in November in Orlando.  Middle and high school students came from all over the state and participated in many different leadership activities from blindfolded trust exercises to Q&A sessions about college, all led by our STARS students.  In the Spring we continued our presence at TSA by helping to judge events and mentor students at the state competition.</p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p>\r\n<p>Presenters: Raquel Safra, Courtney Kallemeres, Louie Garofalo, Katie Smith, Ebe Randeree; FSU</p>\r\n</p>',42,'2011-08-09 15:00:00','2011-08-09 16:00:00',0,NULL,NULL,0,2,0,0,0,0,1,'2011-07-29 19:44:36',89,1,255,255,'Ameri','',0,NULL,'0000-00-00',NULL,NULL),(69,0,8,0,'profile','Partnering with School STEM Initiatives ','Salons D&E','<p> </p>\r\n<p>STARS FSU explored and partnered with local STEM initiatives to facilitate teacher training and student training (technical skills, leadership, and confidence building) in a year-long project. We trained teachers on robotics and social media, configured new technology, and ran two tech clubs at a middle school (a local \"F\" school) and an elementary school (working with gifted and talented kids). A wide range of technology topics were presented including web design, robotics, Photoshop, desktop hardware, and many more in a weekly club format.</p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p>\r\n<p>Presenters: Raquel Safra, Courtney Kallemeres, Louie Garofalo, Katie Smith, Ebe Randeree; FSU</p>\r\n</p>\r\n<p> </p>',42,'2011-08-09 15:00:00','2011-08-09 16:00:00',0,NULL,NULL,0,2,0,0,0,0,1,'2011-07-29 19:46:11',83,1,255,255,'Ameri','',0,NULL,'0000-00-00',NULL,NULL),(70,0,8,0,'profile','Ad Hoc Session','Congressional','<p>\r\n<p style=\"line-height: 15.6pt; background: white;\"><span style=\"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: &quot;Tahoma&quot;,&quot;sans-serif&quot;; color: #333333;\">In addition to the scheduled sessions, you are welcome to organize extended talks, panel discussions or work groups (birds-of-a-feather) in one of the conference’s ad-hoc sessions. These sessions are in response to ideas and issues that have been nagging you or issues and questions that arise during the conference.</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"line-height: 15.6pt; background: white;\"><span style=\"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: &quot;Tahoma&quot;,&quot;sans-serif&quot;; color: #333333;\">To request and ad hoc session, fill out an ad hoc session request form and return it to the registration desk. Ad hoc sessions my be “clinics”, where you bring a problem for which you would like input.  For example, would you like assistance in developing an evaluation tool for a community outreach program? Other suggestions include topics from the conference you would like to discuss further or unscheduled topics that you would like to share at the conference.</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"line-height: 15.6pt; background: white;\"><span style=\"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: &quot;Tahoma&quot;,&quot;sans-serif&quot;; color: #333333;\">Ad hoc session requests will be displayed near the registration tables. Attendees indicate interest in the topic by signing up for the session.  If enough interest is shown, the session will be scheduled in one of the “ad hoc session” rooms. These will be announced at the plenary session in the morning and will be displayed near the registration table.</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"> </p>\r\n</p>',42,'2011-08-09 15:00:00','2011-08-09 16:00:00',0,NULL,NULL,0,1,0,0,0,0,1,'2011-07-29 19:46:43',77,1,40.4265,-111.758,'Ameri','',0,NULL,'0000-00-00',NULL,NULL),(71,0,8,0,'profile','A Panel of Diverse Computing & Technology Professionals: Identifying Barriers and Sharing Strategies for Success ','Boxwood/Dogwood Rooms','<p> </p>\r\n<p>This session is an opportunity for students to participate in a guided, informal panel discussion with area Computing & Technology professionals who come from traditionally underrepresented populations. Panelists will discuss topics such as how they have broken barriers to advancement, the role of collaboration in career success, the importance of a desire to learn, taking appropriate risks, and how to balance work & family life. In this session, these professionals will also share exciting details about how a career in Computing & Technology gives you an opportunity to work daily on the forefront of innovation.</p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p>\r\n<p>Presenter: Felesia Stukes, Central Piedmont Community College</p>\r\n</p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p> </p>',42,'2011-08-09 16:00:00','2011-08-09 17:00:00',0,NULL,NULL,0,2,0,0,0,0,1,'2011-07-29 19:48:01',74,1,255,255,'Ameri','',0,NULL,'0000-00-00',NULL,NULL),(72,0,8,0,'profile','Money and You',' Salons A,B,C','<p> </p>\r\n<p>Finances – money – are important in both our professional and our personal lives.  They ultimately determine success or failure, and what we can or cannot do.  This session will start with basic engineering economics, sometimes called “the time value of money”, and show how it relates to savings, investment, and credit in our personal lives, and system design and project management in our professional lives.  Topics covered include the doubling time of an investment, retirement savings, the insidious effects of small fees, cost of credit, comparing alternative designs, and optimizing life cycle costs. The goal is to replace esoteric analysis with insight and simple calculations to develop intuition to guide behavior.</p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p>Presenter: John Bowles, University of South Carolina</p>\r\n<p> </p>',42,'2011-08-09 16:00:00','2011-08-09 17:00:00',0,NULL,NULL,0,1,1,0,0,0,1,'2011-07-29 19:48:58',77,1,255,255,'Ameri','',0,NULL,'0000-00-00',NULL,NULL),(73,0,8,0,'profile','Marketing through YouTube','Salons D&E  ','<p> </p>\r\n<p>The current generation is surrounded by pervasive multimedia.  The FSU STARS Alliance tapped into that stream in the past (using LinkedIn, Facebook, and Twitter).  Our new focus was to create short video clips describing our programs and outreach initiatives.  We have created videos that highlight the IT and ICT programs as well as the STARS alliance. The videos were used in high school outreach, campus tours, new faculty presentations, school preview/orientation, and on the recruitment website.</p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p>\r\n<p>Presenters: Ashley Rutstein, Brandon Perkins, Louie Garofalo, Katie Smith, Ebe Randeree; Florida State University</p>\r\n</p>\r\n<p> </p>',42,'2011-08-09 16:00:00','2011-08-09 17:00:00',0,NULL,NULL,0,6,0,0,0,0,1,'2011-07-29 19:50:06',92,1,255,255,'Ameri','',0,NULL,'0000-00-00',NULL,NULL),(74,0,8,0,'profile','Social Networking and The STARS Online Community','Salons D&E','<p> </p>\r\n<p>The STARS online community is being developed as a hub for planning activities and sharing experiences throughout STARS. Even with the popularity of online social networking, many current sites still fail to promote a sense of community and allow for meaningful communication between group members. The STARS site will help us investigate how various design features contribute to successful community experiences. In this presentation, I will discuss online community and social networking research, demonstrate the current state of the STARS online community, and highlight the research questions we will be exploring.</p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p>\r\n<p>Presenter: Heather Richter Lipford, University of North Carolina at Charlotte</p>\r\n</p>\r\n<p> </p>',42,'2011-08-09 16:00:00','2011-08-09 17:00:00',0,NULL,NULL,0,6,0,0,0,0,1,'2011-07-29 19:51:11',112,1,255,255,'Ameri','',0,NULL,'0000-00-00',NULL,NULL),(75,0,8,0,'profile','Ad Hoc Session','Congressional','<p>\r\n<p style=\"line-height: 15.6pt; background: white;\"><span style=\"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: &quot;Tahoma&quot;,&quot;sans-serif&quot;; color: #333333;\">In addition to the scheduled sessions, you are welcome to organize extended talks, panel discussions or work groups (birds-of-a-feather) in one of the conference’s ad-hoc sessions. These sessions are in response to ideas and issues that have been nagging you or issues and questions that arise during the conference.</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"line-height: 15.6pt; background: white;\"><span style=\"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: &quot;Tahoma&quot;,&quot;sans-serif&quot;; color: #333333;\">To request and ad hoc session, fill out an ad hoc session request form and return it to the registration desk. Ad hoc sessions my be “clinics”, where you bring a problem for which you would like input.  For example, would you like assistance in developing an evaluation tool for a community outreach program? Other suggestions include topics from the conference you would like to discuss further or unscheduled topics that you would like to share at the conference.</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"line-height: 15.6pt; background: white;\"><span style=\"font-size: 10.5pt; font-family: &quot;Tahoma&quot;,&quot;sans-serif&quot;; color: #333333;\">Ad hoc session requests will be displayed near the registration tables. Attendees indicate interest in the topic by signing up for the session.  If enough interest is shown, the session will be scheduled in one of the “ad hoc session” rooms. These will be announced at the plenary session in the morning and will be displayed near the registration table.</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"> </p>\r\n</p>',42,'2011-08-09 16:00:00','2011-08-09 17:00:00',0,NULL,NULL,0,1,0,0,0,0,1,'2011-07-29 19:51:53',77,1,40.4265,-111.758,'Ameri','',0,NULL,'0000-00-00',NULL,NULL),(76,0,8,0,'profile','Home Team Planning Meetings ','TBA','<p> </p>\r\n<p>Schools who are prepared to begin or continue their STARS Leadership Corps during the upcoming academic year (and do not need the information from STARS New Members workshop) will hold their own Home Team Planning sessions. Planning sessions may be held by an individual school or by a group of regional schools who are coordinating their Corps activities. The purpose of this session is to provide Corps time to plan their upcoming leadership projects and other corps activities.</p>\r\n<p>The organization of this session will be determined by the academic liaisons moderating each group. Each group is encouraged to consider the following for the upcoming academic year: frequency, location and purpose of team meetings; offering of seminars related to STARS central values of Technical Excellence, Leadership, Community, and Service & Civic Engagement; partnership development; organizing your corps into sub-groups or teams; selecting and managing leadership projects, and integrating mentoring into your corps activities.</p>\r\n<p> </p>',42,'2011-08-09 17:00:00','2011-08-09 18:00:00',0,NULL,NULL,0,3,0,0,0,0,1,'2011-07-29 19:53:09',77,1,-5.55,144.583,'Ameri','',0,NULL,'0000-00-00',NULL,NULL),(77,0,8,0,'profile',' STARS ESC Dinner Meeting','Judicial','<p>\r\n<p>This is a meeting of the STARS Alliance Executive Steering committee. <em>Attendance is by invitation only.</em></p>\r\n</p>',42,'2011-08-09 18:00:00','2011-08-09 20:00:00',0,NULL,NULL,0,2,0,0,0,0,0,'2011-07-29 19:54:40',76,1,14.7,121.102,'Ameri','',0,NULL,'0000-00-00',NULL,NULL),(78,0,8,0,'profile','Mentoring Workshop Part III— Closure: Personal Unfoldment & Gifts ','Salon F','<p>\r\n<p>Presenter: Nate Thomas, University of South Florida Polytechnic</p>\r\n</p>',42,'2011-08-09 19:15:00','2011-08-09 21:15:00',0,NULL,NULL,0,1,0,0,0,0,1,'2011-07-29 19:55:50',77,1,13.7713,100.618,'Ameri','',0,NULL,'0000-00-00',NULL,NULL),(79,0,8,0,'profile','Plenary Session','Grand Ballroom','<p>Keynote Speaker: \"Robotics and the Future of Computer Science,” Dave Touretzky, Professor of Computer Science at Carnegie Melon University</p>\r\n<p>\r\n<p>Keynote Speaker: Suzanne Gordon, Chief Information Officer and Vice President of Information Technology at SAS Institute, Inc.</p>\r\n</p>\r\n<p> </p>\r\n<p> </p>',42,'2011-08-10 09:00:00','2011-08-10 11:00:00',0,NULL,NULL,0,3,0,0,0,0,1,'2011-07-29 19:56:47',